column168: Description Of Events

DRIVER WAS DELIVERING TO THE AIR NATIONAL GUARD, WHICH HAS A CLOSED SYSTEM.  THIS MEANS THE DRIVER CANNOT STICK THE TANKS, BUT MUST RELY ON THE INFORMATION SUPPLIED TO HIM BY AIR GUARD PERSONNEL, WHO GET THEIR INFORMATION FROM A VEDDER-ROOT TANK INVENTORY SYSTEM.  THE AIR GUARD PERSONNEL INFORMED THE DRIVER THAT THE TANK HAD ROOM FOR 4000 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER HAD 2969 GALLONS TO DROP.  NEAR THE END OF THE DELIVERY, PRODUCT STARTED TO SPRAY FROM THE TANK VENT PIPE.  THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE DELIVERY PUMP IMMEDIATELY.  APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND WHICH WAS CLEANED UP BY AIR GUARD FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE AIR GUARD HAS TAKEN RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SPILL.

WHEN RECEIVING AN OUTBOUND INSPECTION AT THE RAMP CHECK POINT, THIS TRAILER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A FLUID IT WAS TAKEN TO A SAFE HAVEN FOR ASSESSMENT. BNSF AND SHIPPER'S CONTRACTOR RESPONDERS EVALUATED THE SHIPMENT. NO MAJOR SHIFTING WAS NOTED AS TRAILER CONTENTS APPEARED OK. THREE 55 GALLON DRUMS WERE FOUND STRETCH WRAPPED TOGETHER IN THE FRONT RIGHT CORNER. TWO DRUMS HAD WORN THROUGH THEIR LOWER ROLLING HOOPS AT THE POINTS OF CONTACT. DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED IN OVERPACKS. PRODUCT EVAPORATED RAPIDLY AND LEFT NO RESIDUAL. AN ESTIMATED 20 GALLONS WAS LOST FROM EACH DRUM. INBOUND TRAIN: Q-NYLA1-29.

column14: RR YARD AT LA GRANGE RD
column168: WHILE CONDUCTING ROUTINE YARD INSPECTION, A FRA INSPECTOR FOUND THIS TANK CAR LEAKING PRODUCT. BNSF AND CONSIGNEE RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE LIQUID VALVE WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED. THE HANDLE REQUIRED ABOUT 3/8" FURTHER TRAVEL TO BE PROPERLY POSITIONED. IN ADDITION, THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TURN LOOSE. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE PLUG BEFORE IT WAS FULLY TIGHTENED. THE CAR WAS HELD FOR OBSERVATION AFTER APPLYING ABSORBENT PADS, THEN RELEASED TO SPOT AT THE CONSIGNEE. A SMALL PORTION OF ONE QUART RELEASED DRIPPED FROM THE CAR, BUT ALL PRODUCT EVAPORATED RAPIDLY.

SHIPPER THEN DECONTAMINATED THE TANK CAR SHELL.  AFTER REPAIRS AND DECON WERE COMPLETED THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION AT 0540hrs ON JULY 16,1997.

THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE IMMEDIATE RAIL AREA AND PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERED ONTO THE TANK TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALS OF HCL WAS SPILLED.  NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS WERE REPORTED. THE AREA IS BEING CLEANED UP BY RESPONSE CREW.

column168: DRIVER OF JOHN HEYOB OIL CO TRUCK WAS NORTHBOUND ON PADDYS RUN ROAD.  THE DRIVER DID NOT STOP FOR RAILROAD TRACKS THAT CROSS THE ROAD REQUIRED BY LAW. THE DRIVER WAS THEN STRUCK BY A EASTBOUND CSX TRAIN, CAUSING THE TRUCK TO GET STRUCK IN THE LEFT FRONT END.  AFTER IMPACT THE TRUCK WAS ROLLED ON ITS RIGHT SIDE, CAUSING A SPILL OF AROUND 800 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL.  CLEAN UP WAS IMMEDIATELY PUT INTO ACTION, AFTER THE INITIAL REPORT.  DRIVER WAS DISMISSED FROM HIS POSITION BECAUSE OF PREVIOUS CONVICTION FOR THE SAME VIOLATION.

I RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  LOOSE CAP CAUSED DAMAGE.  I  FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE GUIDELINES, SOLIDIFIED AND PROCESSED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE MATERIAL.  PLACED IN BAG FOLLOWING UPS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  I  WORE THE PROPER PPE ISP CARD FILLED OUT.  ORIGIN BUS DEVL MANAGER SHOULD FOLLOW-UP WITH THE SHIPPER.  CUSTOMER SHOULD TIGHTEN CAPS.
NO REMARKS

DISCOVERED LEAKING PACKAGE IN HAZ MAT CAGE AT THE BEGINNING OF NOONDAY SHIFT.  USED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS TO DETERMINE PROPER CLEAN UP PROCEDURE.  CLEANED UP AND CONTAINED ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WHILE USING ALL PPE.  ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN PLASTIC BAG AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.  ALL SALVAGEABLE MATERIAL WAS REPACKAGED AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

JEFF PROCESSED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL IN THE DMP.  ALL SALVAGEABLE MATERIAL WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  IGNITION SOURCES WERE KEPT AWAY.

column168: AT ABOUT 1830 CHARLES BREMNER WAS LOADING THREE CRATES OF CORROSIVE MATERIALS CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY. I EXPLAINED TO HIM THE CAO LABEL HAD TO BE ON THE LOW SIDE OF THE PALLET. I WENT OVER TO INSURE THAT HE WAS LOADING IT CORRECTLY AND NOTICED THAT HE HAD ONE CRATE WRONG. I TOLD HIM TO LOAD IT CORRECTLY. A FEW MINUTES LATER I HEARD A NOISE AND SAW THE CRATE ON THE FLOOR AND TIPPED OVER. THE TOP OF THE CRATE WAS BROKEN OPENED AND THE PIECE INSIDE WAS STARTING TO COME OUT. WE THEN FLIPPED IT UPRIGHT AND THEN IT STARTED TO LEAK ACID ON THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR. THE CRATE WAS TAKEN OUTSIDE AND THE WHOLE SHIPMENT WAS HELD BACK. LATER I ASKED CHARLES WHAT HAD HAPPEN AND HE TOLD THAT HE DID NOT HAVE HIS FORKLIFT BLADES COMPLETELY UNDERNEATH THE CRATE AND THAT HE MOVED IT TO THE EDGE OF THE PALLET. HE ALSO SAID THAT HE PUT PUNCTURE HOLE IN IT WHEN IT TIPPED OVER. LONNIE HINES ALSO STATED THAT HE DID NOT HAVE HIS BLADES UNDERNEATH IT COMPLETELY AND THAT HE WAS TELLING HIM TO GO UNDER IT MORE. ON THE EVENING OF JULY 17, 1997, FACILITY TECHNICIANS WERE PUMPING FUELS BLENDABLE LIQUIDS INTO A VACUUM TANKER. WHILE PUMPING, ONE OF THE HOSE SPILT CAUSING THE TANKER TO LOSE VACUUM AND APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO THE LOADING DOCK AREA. THE VALVE ON THE TANKER WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF AND A BERM OF FLOOR DRY WAS PLACED DOWN HILL FROM THE SPILL MATERIAL. THE MATERIAL WAS THEN ABSORBED USING FLOOR DRY AND THE FLOOR DRY AND THE BERM WERE PLACED INTO THREE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS. THE AREA WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED WAS THEN CLEANED USING AN ALKALINE DETERGENT SOLUTION. THIS MATERIAL WAS ALSO CONTAINERIZED FOR LATER DISPOSAL.

WHILE LOADING AT FLINT INK LOADING DOCK, THE DRIVER STRUCK A METAL POLE CAUSING THE GATE VALVE TO RELEASE APPROXIMATELY 345 GALLONS OF PRINTERS INK. THE NEW ALBANY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. FLINT INK AND DENNY'S TRANSPORT PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP. A DAM WAS BUILT TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND APPROXIMATELY 295 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AND PLACED INTO SIX (6) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS. THE REMAINING FIFTY (50) GALLONS WAS DRIED UP ON THE FLOOR DUE TO EXPOSURE TO THE AIR. THE SIX (6) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF PRINTER INK WERE HELD AT FLINT INK AND THE PRODUCT WAS RECYCLED. NO FURTHER ACTION IS PLANNED AT THIS TIME.

column168: DRIVER WAS ALERTED BY FOLLOWING MOTORIST THAT A FINE SPRAY OF PRODUCT HAD GOTTEN ONTO HIS PICKUP TRUCK AT THE INTERSECTION WHEN THE TRUCK STARTED UP FROM A STOP.  THE DRIVER INVESTIGATED AND FOUND THAT 4 BOLTS HAD WORKED LOOSE THAT HELD THE FIRST SHUT OFF VALVE TO TOP OF TANK TRAILER.  DRIVER TIGHTENED THESE BACK INTO THEIR CORRECT POSITION.  IN A CHECK OF THE HIGHWAY SURFACE, THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF SPILLED PRODUCT. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT TO BE CLEANED FROM ROADWAY.  THE PICKUP TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO A NEARBY CARWASH AND CLEANED.  THERE WERE NO KNOWN INJURIES. THERE WAS NO OTHER KNOWN PROPERTY DAMAGE.

AS THIS TRAILER CONTAINED HM HE IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE LEAK TO THE DOCK SUPERVISOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CLOCK SUPERVISOR, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A POISON 6.1 WAS LEAKING. TRAILER WAS SECURED IN AN OPEN ARE OF THE YARD AND CLAY ABSORBENT WAS APPLIED TO SPILL ON REAR OF TRAILER AND BELOW LEAK PER HM CONTAINMENT GUIDE. LAIDLAW HM TEAM WAS THEN CALLED TO SCENE FOR CLEANUP.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER ENCOUNTERED ROUGH ROAD SURFACE AND A MECHANICAL FAILURE OCCURRED ON TRAILER UNDER CARRIAGE CAUSING ROLLOVER ACCIDENT.  PRODUCT VAPORS COULD BE DETECTED BY FIRST RESPONDERS BUT THERE WAS NO SIGN OF LIQUID LEAKAGE.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED INTO A DIFFERENT TANK TRAILER.  CARRIER SENT 4 TRAINED PERSONS, SHIPPER SENT 8 TRAINED PERSONS, AND CARRIER HIRED PROTERRA ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY OF COLUMBUS, OHIO. TRANSFER OF PRODUCT OPERATION WAS UNEVENTFUL.  NO PRODUCT WAS ABLE TO BE DETECTED ON THE PAVED SURFACE.  NONE ON GROUND. NONE TO CLEANUP.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER NOTICED SPILL.  AT THIS POINT IN TIME WE CHECKED WITH BILL OF LADING TO CHECK WHAT KIND OF MATERIAL IT WAS.  ONCE IDENTIFIED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM DOCK AND PLACED IN YARD WITH TRAILER DOOR SLIGHTLY OPEN FOR VENTILATION. CLEAN UP CREW WAS CONTACTED.

WHILE ANOTHER SHIPPER WAS LOADING THEIR FREIGHT WITH A FORKLIFT, THEY ACCIDENTALLY PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  IT WAS REALIZED WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED BACK AT THE TERMINAL. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THE SPILL CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.

AT 3:42 AM ON WEDNESDAY JULY 16, 1997, I WAS NOTIFIED AT MY HOME OF A SULFURIC ACID SPILL AT OUR SOUTH DOCK FACILITY. THE SULFURIC ACID WAS A MIXTURE THAT WAS LEAKING FROM TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS IN THE NOSE OF A TRAILER. AFTER ARRIVING AT THE TERMINAL I FOUND THAT THE MAJORITY OF 3RD SHIFT DOCK WORKERS HAD BEEN EVACUATED AND SENT TO AN AREA OUTSIDE THE TERMINAL. WHEN I ARRIVED INSIDE TWO DOCK SUPERVISORS (QUALIFIED AS HAZ/MAT TECHNICIANS) WERE ON THE SCENE NEUTRALIZING THE AREA INSIDE THE TRAILER WITH SODA ASH. THE DRIVER OF THE TOW MOTOR HAD PUNCTURED TWO PLASTIC GALLON DRUMS THAT WERE LOADED SIDE BY SIDE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE TOWMOTOR OPERATOR HAD LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE WHEN A PIECE OF WOOD BECAME LODGED UNDER THE BACK END OF THE TOWMOTOR. AS A RESULT HE WAS UNABLE TO PULL THE TOWMOTOR FORKS FROM THE INSIDE OF THE CONTAINER. WE WERE QUITE FORTUNATE THAT THIS HAPPENED BECAUSE THE FORKS ACTED AS A PLUG, PREVENTING COMPLETE LOSS OF THE MATERIAL. THE FORK HOLES WERE AT THE VERY BOTTOM OUTSIDE AREA.  INFO TRAC WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY SENT A SULFURIC ACID MSDS OVER THE FAX WITHIN MINUTES. SHORTLY AFTER RECEIVING THIS FAX, INFO TRAC CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND WE WERE SENT THE CORRECT MSDS ON THIS (SULFURIC ACID MIXTURE). THE MSDS WAS ANALYZED AND TWO OF OUR DOCK SUPERVISORS SUITED UP IN CLASS A AND B. IT WAS DECIDED THAT WE WOULD TOW THE TOW MOTOR OUT OF THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER BECAUSE OF A SECONDARY COMBUSTIBLE GAS HAZARD FROM THE MATERIAL.

TRAILER WAS LOADED ON 07-18-97 AT EASTMAN CHEMICAL IN KINGSPORT, TN.  AFTER LOADING, THE TRAILER WAS BROUGHT TO THE KINGSPORT TENNESSEE TERMINAL WHERE IT WAS PARKED IN THE YARD TO AWAIT TRANSPORT TO ASHLAND CHEMICAL IN MOBILE, ALABAMA. WHEN THE MECHANIC HOOKED THE TRAILER UP, PRIOR TO DISPATCH, HE NOTICED DRIPPING FROM THE WEEP HOLES BETWEEN COMPARTMENTS #4 AND #5.  THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT AND DELIVERED AS SCHEDULED.  THE SPILL AMOUNTED TO LESS THAN 1/2 CUP OF PRODUCT.  LATER INVESTIGATION REVEALED PINHOLES IN THE CIRCUMFERENCE WELD AROUND THE HEAD OF THE #5 COMPARTMENT.  THE TRAILER WAS SENT FOR REPAIR.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: FLIGHT 811, 8 JULY 1997 DEPARTED ONTARIO INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT AT 1926 LOCAL TIME.  AFTER TAKEOFF AND ARRIVING TO AN ALTITUDE OF APPROX 15,000 FEET, THE AIRCRAFT WAS PRESSURIZED.  AT THAT TIME THE AIRCREW NOTED A CHEMICAL ODOR, AND THEN THE DECISION WAS MADE TO RETURN TO THE ORIGIN AIRPORT.  UPON REARRIVAL BACK TO THE AIRPORT, APPROPRIATE ON-SITE HAZARDOUS RESPONSE TEAM AND THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT MET THE AIRCRAFT, EVACUATED THE AIRCREW AND CONDUCTED THEIR INITIAL INVESTIGATION.  IT HAD BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE CHEMICAL ODOR (AMMONIA) HAD VENTED IN FLIGHT FROM A CONTAINER LOADED INTO THE P1 POSITION ON THE AIRCRAFT.  IT WAS THEN DETERMINED NOT ONLY TO REMOVE THE HAZARDOUS CARGO BUT INCLUDE THE WHOLE PALLET FOR SAFETY.  UPON EXAMINATION OF THE CARGO AT THE STATION SITE, NO VENTING EXISTED. WHEN OPENING THE OUTER SHIPPING CONTAINER DURING AN FAA INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER PACKAGE CONTAINING AMMONIA HYDROXIDE HAD VENTED AND MINOR SPILLAGE OCCURRED FROM THE FITTING VALVE OF THE CONTAINER.  IMPROPER PACKAGING OF THE INNER CONTAINER ALLOWED THE CONTAINER TO SHIFT DURING ANY MOVEMENT, WHICH ALLOWED SPILLAGE.

column168: WHILE PREPARING TO MAKE A DELIVERY AT A CUSTOMER LOCATION, IT WAS REPORTED THAT A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE SIDE OF THE CARGO TANKERS MAIN SUPPLY VALVE.  DRIP BUCKETS WERE USED TO COLLECT AS MUCH OF THE LEAK AS POSSIBLE.  A GARDEN HOSE WAS USED TO IMMEDIATELY BEGIN DILUTING THE PRODUCT SPILLED.  THE DELIERY WAS MADE TO EMPTY THE TANKER.  THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE CAUSED BY A WORN RUBBER COATED METAL SPACER (LARGE WASHER) BETWEEN THE TOP OF THE VALVE AND THE FLANGE ON THE TANKER DISCHARGE PIPE. THE WORN SPACER ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ENTER AN INSIDE BOLT HOLE ON THE VALVE BODY AND CORRODE THE SIDE UNTIL A HOLE WAS FORMED.  THE COMPANY USED TO INSPECT AND REPAIR RUBBER LINING HAS BEEN TOLD TO INCLUDE ALL SPACERS IN FUTURE WORK.

column168: WHILE INSPECTING CARGO AT TRUCK-STOP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS COMING OUT REAR TRAILER.  THE ILLINOIS STATE POLICE RESPONDED. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH CONSIGNEE WHO IN TURN RESPONDED TO SCENE TO PERFORM CLEAN-UP AND OVERPACKAGING.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT A PALLET HAD BROKEN CAUSING A PUNCTURE TO THE BOTTOM OF ONE DRUM.  THIS RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF FIVE GALLONS OF LIQUID.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND SPILLED LIQUID PICKED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, (REPORT NO. 394238) AND THE ILLINOIS EPA, (REPORT NO. 971223).  LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

ON FRIDAY JULY 25, 1997 AT APPROX 1600 UNOCAL RAIL CAR GATX 49697 PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE SLIGHTLY RELIEVED ITSELF DUE TO PRESSURE IN OUR YARD.  THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE IS ESTIMATED TO BE 60 POUNDS FOR 10 MINUTES.  UPON THE REMEDIATION OF THE HIGH PRESSURE ON THE RAIL CAR, WE REPORTED THE HIGH PRESSURE DISCHARGE TO ANOTHER VESSEL WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE.  AFTER FURTHER REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT IT WAS NOTED THAT THE PRESSURE  RELIEF VALVE WAS SET AT 228 PSI.  LA ROCHE IND INC WILL PAY CLOSER ATTENTION TO WHAT THE RELIEF VALVES ARE RATED AT TO ELIMINATE THIS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: TRAILER BEGAN TO LEAK WHILE PARKED ON THE ACCESS ROAD AT CUSTOMER PLANT. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY LEAKAGE OF THE MATERIAL AT EITHER LOCATION.

DRIVER ASKED AN OPERATOR FOR ASSISTANCE. OPERATOR CLOSED THE MANUAL RISER VALVE AND ASSUMED THE DRIVER CLOSED THE TRUCK INTERNAL VALVE BUT HE HAD NOT. A PIECE OF INTERNAL LINER OF THE LOADING HOSE WAS LODGE BETWEEN THE COUPLER AND DRYBREAK.  THE DRIVER AND OPERATOR WERE SPRAYED WITH GASOLINE, BOTH TOOK SHOWERS AND CHANGED CLOTHES AND ARE OK. ALL THE GASOLINE WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE LINED LOAD RACK CONCRETE CONTAINMENT PAD AND RETURNED VIA A STRIP DRAIN AND DOWNGRADED TO TRANSMIX.  THE LOAD RACK WAS WASHED DOWN AND EVERYTHING WAS CONTAINED.  THE PLUS LOADING ARM WAS TAGGED OUT OF SERVICE ON THE SOUTH END OF LANE #2.  AN INCIDENT INVESTIGATION WILL BE CONDUCTED.

column168: WHILE TRAVELING ON ROUTE 35 NEAR SAYERVILLE, NJ, THE DRIVER NOTICED VAPOR COMING FROM THE REAR CABINET OF THE TRAILER CONTAINING NITROGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID.  THE DRIVER TURNED OFF THE ROAD INTO THE BACK OF A COMMERCIAL AREA TO INSPECT THE TRAILER.  HE FOUND THAT THE MAIN FILL VALVE WAS LEAKING OUT THE CAPPED END PIECE.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND BY APPLYING AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WATER TO THE VALVE BODY, THE VALVE WAS ABLE TO BE FULLY CLOSED THEREBY STOPPING THE LEAK. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER.  AFTER THE FILL VALVE WAS WARMED AND FULLY CLOSED, THE ESCAPE OF PRODUCT CEASED AND THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CONTINUE SAFELY ON HIS WAY WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT.  BECAUSE, THE INCIDENT IS ATTRIBUTED TO THE DRIVER'S FAILURE TO PROPERLY CLOSE THE FILL VALVE AFTER LOADING, THE DRIVER WILL BE COUNSELLED CONCERNING THIS IMPORTANT ASPECT OF VEHICLE LOADING AND TRANSPORTATION.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT STATED THAT AS HE NEARED VICTORIA, TX, ON HIGHWAY 77 APPROACHING A BRIDGE, HE DOZED AT THE WHEEL LOST CONTROL WHEN THE VEHICLE STRUCK A GUARD RAIL.  THE TRUCK RODE THE GUARD RAIL FOR APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET BEFORE GOING OVER THE GUARD RAIL AND DOWN THE RIVER BANK WITH THE TRACTOR ENTERING THE RIVER.  THE VEHICLE STAYED UPRIGHT, HOWEVER, EITHER A GUARD RAIL POST OR A TREE DAMAGED THE OUTER VESSEL OF THE TRAILER CAUSING THE TRAILER TO LOOSE THE ANNULAR SPACE VACUUM.  THE LOSS OS VACUUM RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF INSULATING PROPERTIES OF THE TRAILER.  THIS RESULTED IN THE VENTING OF NON-FLAMMABLE ARGON GAS AS THE CRYOGENIC LIQUID WARMED.  THE TRAILER WAS RECOVERED BACK TO THE ROADWAY AND THE REMAINING LIQUID PRODUCT WAS VENTED TO ATMOSPHERE.  THE VEHICLE WAS A TOTAL LOSS AND WILL BE REPLACED.  THE DRIVER'S RECORD WILL BE REVIEWED PENDING PERSONNEL ACTION AND DISCIPLINE AS APPROPRIATE.

column168: DRIVER DROPPED TRAILER ON ITS LEGS IN THE LATE AFTERNOON ON WHAT WAS APPARENTLY A SOFT SPOT IN THE TRUCK TERMINAL YARD.  AFTER SEVERAL HOURS THE GROUND SHIFTED UNDER ONE LEG AND THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER ON ITS SIDE.  THERE WERE SEVERAL LOOSE CLEANOUT CAPS, SEVERAL LOOSE OR OPEN AIR INLET VALVES, AND ONE OF THE 5 DOMES WAS NOT COMPLETELY TIGHT.  PRODUCT WAS SEEPING FROM SEVERAL OPENINGS. DRIVER DELIVERED IN NORMAL MANNER.  THE CUSTOMER PERSONNEL HAD TOTAL CONTROL OF THEIR INDOOR STORAGE TANK - WHICH THE DRIVER NEVER SAW BEFORE OR AFTER THE DELIVERY. DRIVER WAS TOLD TO SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING WHEN THE INDOOR STORAGE OVERFLOWED AT END OF UNLOADING.  THE PLANT PERSONNEL WOULD NOT DISCUSS THE AMOUNT OF THE SPILL AND INFORMED DRIVER THEY WOULD CLEAN UP.  TO BEST OF INFORMATION DRIVER COULD ASCERTAIN, THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

THIS CAUSED THE PUMP TO REMOVE PRODUCT FROM CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK AND PUMP IT INTO THE TANK TRUCK.  THE TANK TRUCK OVERFLOWED OUT THE DOME. CUSTOMER PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP OPERATIONS.  THERE WERE NO KNOWN INJURIES.  ALL OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CAPTURED BY THE CUSTOMER IN A CONTAINMENT AREA.

THE AUGUSTA, KY POLICE REPORTED A TRAIN PASSING THROUGH  TOWN HAD A STRONG ODOR. TRAIN WAS INSPECTED AS IT PAST 2 MAINTENANCE CREWS AND THEY REPORTED BEING ABLE TO SMELL A "PROPANE ODOR". column168: DRIVER DEPARTED FROM ORIGIN AT 0710 ON 7/12/97. HE ARRIVED AT THE DESTINATION (8615 MANCHESTER) AT 0745. AS HE EXITED THE CAB OF HIS TRACTOR, THE TRAILER'S PRESSURE RELEASE DEVICE ACTIVATED WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF 15 GALLONS  OF CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.D.S. (SULFURIC ACID/ACRYLIC ACID). THE PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY AT THE PLANT ENTRANCE. THE DRIVER UNLOADED THE TRAILER AND WASHED THE PRODUCT OFF THE TRAILER'S EXTERIOR. THE TRAILER WAS SENT TO SERVICE TRANSPORT COMPANY'S HOUSTON TERMINAL WHERE THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS REMOVED AND BENCH TESTED. THE TESTS CONFIRMED THE VALVE OPERATED PROPERLY. THE MANUFACTURER'S SPECIFICATION FOR THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE IS 65.5 PSIG. THE SHIPPER IS CURRENTLY INVESTIGATING THE INCIDENT. THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE CONCRETE SURFACE AND PROPER DISPOSAL IS PENDING (TEXAS WASTE CODE NUMBER REQUIRED).

column168: DETREX CORPORATION'S FACILITY WAS FLOODED DURING A STROM EVENTON JULY 23, 1997. A SECOND FLOOD WAS EXPECTED TO OCCUR THE SAME DAY. DURING A PERIOD WHEN WATERS SUBSIDED, FACILITY PERSONNEL ENTERED THE FACILITY TO REMOVE ALL OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE AS REQUIRED UNDER OUR PERMIT AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE TREATMENT FACILITY. DUE TO THE LIMITED WINDOW OF OPPORTUNITY, BASED ON WEATHER FORECASTS, THE TRUCK WAS LOADED AND TRANSPORTED TO A SAFE HAVRN AT ANOTHER HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE FACILITY (ASHLAND CHEMICAL). DURING TRANSPORTATION SOME MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE DOME OF THE TANKER WHEN IT CAME TO A STOP AT THE FREEWAY EXIT. EMPLOYEE NOTICED RELEASE UPON ENTERING FACILITY. SAND PLACED ON ROAD TO ABSORB MINOR AMOUNT NOT CONTAINED IN DOME AREA AROUND LID.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM AQUA CLEAR INDUSTRIES LOCATED AT 2550 9TH AVENUE, IN WATERVLIET, NY TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL. DURING THE COURSE OF THIS TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. (CHCI) LOCATED AT 761 MIDDLE STREET IN BRISTOL, CT IN ORDER TO TRANSFER MATERIAL FROM HIS VEHICLE TO ANOTHER VEHICLE. DURING THE TRANSFER OPERATION, CHCI PERSONNEL USED A DRUM HANDLING DEVICE KNOWN AS A "PARROT BEAK" TO PICKUP A DRUM BY UPPER LIP FOR MOVEMENT OF THE DRUM FROM ONE VEHICLE TO ANOTHER. ONCE THE DRUM WAS OFF THE FLOOR OF THE VEHICLE, THE METAL TOP OF THE DRUM SEPARATED FROM THE FIBERBOARD WALL RESULTING IN A RELEASE TO THE ENVIRONMENT. CHCI PERSONNEL INITIATED A CLEANUP OPERATION. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PLACED ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE DRIVER INSPECTED ALL CONTAINERS FOR INTEGRITY. CHCI PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO USE AN ALTERNATE METHOD WHEN MOVING FIBERBOARD CONTAINERS.

BASED ON ICAO 9.1, CHAPTER 2-9-1, AN OTHER REGULATED SUBSTANCE IS ANY MATERIAL WHICH HAS ANESTHETIC, NOXIOUS, OR SIMILAR PROPERTIES SUCH AS COULD CAUSE EXTREME ANNOYANCE OR DISCOMFORT TO A FLIGHT CREW MEMBER SO AS TO PREVENT THE CORRECT PERFORMANCE OF ASSIGNED DUTIES. BASED ON THE FACT THAT AN AIRCRAFT IS A PRESSURIZED ENVIRONMENT, WE BELIEVE THAT THIS "VOMIT SMELLING" LIQUID WOULD FALL UNDER THE AUSPICES OF AN OTHER REGULATED MATERIAL. column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRANSPORT WAS WESTBOUND ON I-40 WHEN RIGHT FRONT STEER TIRE BLEW OUT.  TRUCK VEERED TO RIGHT AND RAN ALONG THE SHOULDER FOR APPROX 200 FT.  AS DRIVER WAS TRYING TO REGAIN CONTROL, WEIGHT SHIFTED CAUSING ROLLOVER AND TANK RUPTURE.  WHEN TRUCK CAME TO REST ON EDGE OF ROAD, DRIVER EXITED AND UNIT IMMEDIATELY BURNED RESULTING IN TOTAL LOSS OF TRUCK AND PRODUCT.  MOST OF THE GASOLINE BURNED WITH SOME IMMEDIATE CONTAMINATION. SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS ON SITE WITHIN 1 HOUR AND BEGAN IMMEDIATE CLEAN UP.  HAZ MAT WASTE MANIFEST NOT COMPLETE AT TIME OF THIS REPORT.

column168: THE PALLET CONTAINING THE METHYL ETHYL KETONE (MEK) WAS ALREADY UNLOADED AND SITTING ON THE FLOOR OF THE CUSTOMER'S WAREHOUSE.  WHEN THE CUSTOMER UNLOADED THE OTHER PALLET OF PRODUCT FROM OUR TRUCK, HE STUCK THE MEK DRUM WITH A FORK WHEN HE WAS SITTING THE PALLET ON THE FLOOR.  OUR DRIVER ROLLED THE DRUM OVER AS SOON AS HE SAW THE PUNCTURE TO MINIMIZE THE SPILL THE CUSTOMER HANDLED THE CLEANUP.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WE HAVE INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO WATCH CAREFULLY DURING UNLOADING AND WARN CUSTOMER IF HE SEES A SITUATION ARISING SIMILAR TO THIS.

column168: A FREIGHT TRAIN FROM THE EASTERN MAINE RAILWAY WAS PULLING INTO THE CANADIAN AMERICAN RAILROAD YARD AT BROWNVILLE JCT FOR INTERCHANGE DELIVERY. THE COMBINATION OF WORN SWITCH POINT AND A WORN WHEEL FLANGE RESULTED IN THE DERAILMENT OF TWO EMPTY LPG TANKCARS. A CDAC EMPLOYEE WITNESSED THE DERAILMENT AND PROCEEDED TO CONTACT DISPATCHER AND SUPERVISORS. VARIOUS NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE DEP, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES. AFTER DERAILMENT WAS CLEANED UP, BAD SWITCH WAS CHANGED. SIDE OF TANK CAR WAS RUBBED AND DENTED BY BOXCAR. NO PUNCTURE OR RUPTURES TO THE TANK OCCURRED. PRESSURE REMAINED STABLE AT 80#, SAME AS WHEN LEFT THE REFINERY.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE DRIVER WAS AT THE GAS STATION UNLOADING THE LAST COMPARTMENT. AS HE OPENED THE VALVE ON THE TRUCK TO BEGIN UNLOADING. PRODUCT (GASOLINE) BEGAN SPRAYING OUR THE SIDES OF THE PRODUCT HOSE AT THE CONNECTION WITH THE DISCHARGE PIPING OF THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT AND CLEANED UP THE 1 GALLON SPILL WITH SPILL PADS.  THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY THE DRIVER'S IMPROPER INSTALLATION OF A NEW 4" GASKET IN THE DISCHARGE PIPE ON HIS PRIOR DELIVERY.  THE GASKET WAS CROOKED (TWISTED) AT THE TOP AND DIDN'T PROVIDE A GOOD SEAL WHEN THE HOSE WAS INSERTED. MEMO TO ALL DRIVERS ON THIS PROBLEM.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS DRIVING SOUTH DOWN HILL ON SOUTH HWY 23  JUST SOUTH OF LAMONT, WA.  DRIVER COMING AROUND BLIND CORNER AT APPROX. 45 MPH WHEN AN UNIDENTIFIED PEDESTRIAN VEHICLE WAS ACROSS THE CENTERLINE BY 2-3 FEET.  ATI DRIVER, FRANK PETERS SWERVED TO MISS THIS PEDESTRIAN VEHICLE AND THE TRAILER LEFT THE ROADWAY STRIKING A CULVERT IN THE DITCH AND OVERTURNING ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE.  THE ACCIDENT CAUSE THE WELD BETWEEN THE FRONT BULKHEAD AND THE SHELL TO SPLIT AND DISCHARGE A PORTION OF THE LOAD.  AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT THE CLEAN UP PROCEDURES ARE STILL UNDER REVIEW BECAUSE THE EXCAVATION MIGHT AFFECT THE INTEGRITY OF THE ROAD AND THE SHOULDER.  I CAN BE REACHED FOR FURTHER QUESTIONS AT 541-383-2255.

column168: WHILE DERAMPING TANK CONTAINER SFTU 21019 AT ITS DESTINATION RAIL TERMINAL, LIQUID WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE DRAIN/OVERFLOW PIPING.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE UNIT AND FOUND THE PRESSURE LINE, A SMALL BALL VALVE, TO BE IN THE OPEN POSITION.  IN ADDITION, THE CHICAGO FITTING/CAP WAS NOT IN PLACE.  AN ESTIMATED FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED PRIOR TO CORRECTION OF THE DEFICIENCIES.

RESIDUE TANK CAR FOUND RELEASING VAPOR WHILE IN YARD TRACK.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED TANK CAR UTLX 96945 AND FOUND VAPOR LEAKING FROM 'A' END LIQUID LINE VALVE. VALVE WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED; HOWEVER, CLOSING THE VALVE DID NOT COMPLETELY STOP THE LEAK.  THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED ACCOUNT LOOSE.  THIS COMBINATION STOPPED THE LEAKAGE. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED LOOSE VALVE PLUGS ON THE 'B' END LIQUID LINE AND VAPOR VALVES.  CAR WAS FORWARDED FOR PURGING AND VALVE REPLACEMENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: THE CREW ON TRAIN H-HOUBARA-26A OBSERVED A CONTINUOUS RELEASE OF VAPOR FROM THIS CRYOGENIC TANK CAR, ACFX 13204.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND BNSF RESPONDERS WERE CONTACTED.  ALTHOUGH THE VENTING HAD STOPPED, ICING WAS NOTED ON THE PIPING TO AND AT THE 25 PSI SAFETY VALVE.  THE 15 PSI ROAD VALVE WAS NOT FUNCTIONAL AS A CUT OFF VALVE LEADING TO IT WAS CLOSED.  PRESSURE READING VARIED BETWEEN THE TWO GAUGES PRESENT. AFTER A PHONE CONFERENCE, THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED TO ADJUST THE PRESSURE GAUGES AND REDUCE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE FROM 16 PSI TO 12 PSI.  THE SHIPPER CONSIDERS THIS CAR TO HAVE BEEN VENTING EXCESSIVELY.

TANK CAR UTLX 99065, RESIDUE SHIPMENT OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS REPORTED AS LEAKING VAPOR WHILE IN YARD TRACK 7121 FROM INBOUND TRAIN H-BARSSBI-25A. BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE CAR AND FOUND VAPOR LEAKING AT THE LIQUID VALVE.  THE PACKING AROUND THE VALVE STEM WAS COMPRESSED BY TIGHTENING THE LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT.  THE LEAKAGE WAS STOPPED.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: A CITIZEN REPORTED CAR GATX 26742, A LOAD OF PROPANE, VENTING TO THE ATMOSPHERE. BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED LOAD AND CONFIRMED RELEASE THROUGH THE 280 PSI SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE CONSIGNEE FOR IMMEDIATE DELIVERY AND UNLOADING.  A SPECIAL SWITCH MOVE WAS MADE TO EXPEDITE DELIVERY. THE CONSIGNEE INDICATED THE CAR WAS SLIGHTLY OVERFILLED.  PRESSURE READINGS AFTER SPOTTING WERE 260 PSI VAPOR, 270 PSI LIQUID (11 INCHES OF OUTAGE).  AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS 105F.

column168: WHILE INSPECTING OUTBOUND TRAIN H-BARRICA-27A, CAR INSPECTORS HEARD A HISSING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA OF THIS CAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE RESIDUE SHIPMENT AND FOUND A TAG ON THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING LATCH BAR THAT INDICATED THAT THE CAR'S SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE.  ESCAPING VAPOR WAS NOTED COMING FROM THE SRV. UPON DISMANTLING THE SRV, ONE 'O' RINGS WERE REPLACED AS A PRECAUTION.  THE CAR WAS STENCILED TO INDICATE A LEAKING VALVE AND WAS ROUTED TO ITS HOME SHOP.  THE SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE HAS RECEIVED A COPY OF THIS REPORT.

column62: Abrasion; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: UPON ARRIVAL OF TRAIN P-CHILACI-25A, THIS 20' CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT ONTO DECK OF FLAT CAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED LOAD AN NOTED WET PALLET IN THE SECOND TIER, BUT LOAD BRACING APPEARED ADEQUATE.  ABSORBENT WAS APPLIED AND THE UNIT WAS DERAMPED AND TAKEN TO THE DOCK.  TWO LEAKING DRUMS WERE FOUND: (A) BOTH ROLLING HOOPS WORN THROUGH ACCOUNT CONTACT WITH ADJACENT DRUM.  (B) SIDEWALL WORK THROUGH ACCOUNT CONTACT WITH ADJACENT DRUMS.  HOLES IN BOTH DRUMS WERE PATCHED, THE DRUMS PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. HARDENED PRODUCTS WERE CHIPPED FROM THE CONTAINER FLOOR AND FLAT CAR.

A BULK BUTANOL TANK WAS OVERFILLED.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND COLLECTED FROM A CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  THE RECOVERED MATERIAL WILL BE USED AS A RAW MATERIAL.  A RAINSTORM JUST AFTER THE RECOVERY OF THE 320 GALLONS RESULTED IN 2000 GALLONS OF WATER CONTAMINATED BY 20 GALLONS OF BUTANOL.  AGAIN, ALL MATERIAL WAS SECURELY HELD BY SECONDARY CONCRETE CONTAINMENT.  THE WATER/BUTANOL BLEND WAS MOVED TO RCRA-APPROVED HOLDING TANK AND DISPOSED OF AS A UO31 WASTE.  THE DRIVER HAS A CDL LICENCE WITH A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ENDORSEMENT.  HE HAS BEEN EMPLOYEED FOR 11 YEARS WITHOUT INCIDENT.  HE HAS BEEN ALERTED TO HIS FAILURE TO FOLLOW INSTRUCTIONS TO CONSTANTLY MONITOR HIS LOADING/ UNLOADING ACTIVITIES.  HIS PAPERWORK PREPARED BY PURCHASING WILL NOTIFY THE DRIVEROF THE PROPER TANK TO FILL.

THE REAR TOTE DUE TO THE LIQUID NATURE OF THE MATERIAL INSIDE ROLLED UP AND OVER THE BRACING SUPPLIED BY THE SHIPPER AND INSTALLED BY THE DRIVER.  THE TOTE LANDED UPSIDE DOWN AND BEGAN LEAKING FOR THE FILLING OPENING.
column172: Composite, with a rigid plastic inner receptacle for liquids and a steel outer packaging

column168: TRAILER 60636 WAS LOADED AT EASTMAN CHEMICAL IN BEDFORD PARK AND THEN PARKED AT THE MARKHAM TERMINAL TO AWAIT TRANSPORT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, AN ODOR AND MOISTURE WERE DISCOVERED ON THE TRAILER FRAME WHICH WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE PRODUCT THAT WAS IN THE TANK.  A CONTAINER WAS PLACED UNDER THE FRAME TO CATCH ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE AND THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.  THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT SPILLED EVAPORATED.  NO OTHER CLEANUP WAS REQUIRED AT THE TERMINAL.  THE TANK WAS LATER EXAMINED CLOSELY AND PRESSURE TESTED.  NO HOLES, CRACKS OR DEFECTS WERE FOUND.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A LOOSE CLEAN OUT CAP.

OUR VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A MINOR SPILL. THE VEHICLE WAS PARKED FOR THE NIGHT AT A HOTEL WITH A LOAD OF DRUMS. THE NEXT MORNING THE DRIVER DISCOVERED SOME LEAKAGE FROM THE BACK OF THE TRUCK. HE CONTAINED THE LEAKAGE WITH CLAY ABSORBENT. THE TRUCK WAS THEN OPENED AND THE LEAKING DRUM IDENTIFIED AND OVERPACKED. IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM SEAM. THE DRUM WAS IN GOOD CONDITION OTHERWISE. MOST LIKELY THE VIBRATION FROM TRANSPORTATION CAUSED THE SEAM TO WEAKEN AND LEAK. THE DRIVER WILL MORE CLOSELY INSPECT THIS TYPE OF DRUM IN THE FUTURE TO REDUCE THE CHANCE OF REPEAT INCIDENTS. THE MATERIAL IS LOADED INTO THE TOP IF THE TANKER FROM A STATIONARY TANKER.  THE 6000 GALLON TANKER IS FILLED TO CAPACITY IN JUST THREE MINUTES DUE TO THE HIGH PRESSURE OF THE WASTE FLOWING FROM THE STATIONARY TANK. SOMETIMES WHEN AN AIR POCKET DEVELOPED IN THE HOSE FILING  THE CARGO TANK, THIS CAUSES MATERIAL TO SPLASH OUT OF THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK WHEN THE AIR POCKETS IS FORCED INTO THE CARGO TANK. THIS IS HOW THE SPILL OCCURRED.  THE AREA WHERE THE CARGO TANK IS FILLED DOES NOT HAVE ANY CONTAINMENT. THE DRIVER SHOULD BE ABLE TO CONTROL THE FLOW OF MATERIAL FROM THE STATIONARY TANKER INTO THE CARGO TANK.  THE AREA SHOULD ALSO HAVE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT TO PREVENT RELEASE OFF THE ASPHALT PAVEMENT.

ALL APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  INSPECTION BY CONRAIL TRAIN CREW AND POLICE FOUND TANK CAR GLNX34238 VENTING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA.  LOCAL BUSINESS' AND HIGHWAYS RT 61 AND BYPASS SHUT DOWN.  VENTING CONTINUED FROM AT LEAST REPORTED TIME 1745 HOURS UNTIL 2000 HOURS.  LOCAL FIRE DEPT AND BERKS COUNTY HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM APPLIED LARGE QUANTITIES OF WATER THROUGHOUT VENTING PERIOD.  AREA AROUND CAR AND TOP OF CAR METERED WITH CITY CGI BERKS COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM NOTING "0" READINGS.  AT APPROX 2230 HRS OUTAGE GAUGED VIA MAGNETIC GAUGE ROD ON CAR BY CONRAIL'S MANAGER HAZMAT FIELD SERVICES AND DOE SENIOR INSPECTOR W J OERTLY NOTING 7 3/4 INCHES OF OUTAGE.  INSPECTION OF HOUSING AREA AND VALVES/FITTINGS INSIDE SAME, COULD NOT REVEAL SOURCE OF RELEASE.  CAR RELEASED PRODUCT AGAIN, LASTED APPROX 3 MINUTES THEN CEASED.  NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT FOR REMAINDER OF INCIDENT. AT APPROX 0630 HRS ON JULY 16, 1997 4 TANK TRUCK LOADS (3 AT 90%, 1 AT 25% OF TRUCK'S CAPACITY) WERE TRANSFERRED FROM TANK CAR.  AT APPROX 1305 HRS TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED. LOCAL HIGHWAYS RE-OPENED BY BERKS COUNTY AFTER 1ST TANK TRUCK LOAD COMPLETED JULY 16, 1997 AT 0845 HOURS.  RAILROAD WAS BACK IN SERVICE AT APPROX 1330 HOURS.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRANSPORTING CRUDE OIL FROM BAKERSFIELD, CA TO SOUTH GATE CA.  WHEN AN UNKNOWN VEHICLE VEERED INTO HIS LANE HEAD-ON. OUR DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID THIS VEHICLE AND IN DOING SO CAUSED THE TRAILER OF HIS VEHICLE TO VEER OFF THE ROADWAY, CATCHING THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY AND CAUSING ROLL-OVER AND SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 3500 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL ON THE ROADWAY AND ADJACENT FIELD.  OUR OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED ALONG WITH ALL OTHER REQUIRED AUTHORITIES AS TO THE ACCIDENT AND SPILL.  THE SITE WAS CLEANED BY ADVANCED CLEANUP TECHNOLOGIES INC. -4548 WESLEY LANE BAKERSFIELD CA WITH THE WASTE DELIVERED TO MCKITTRICK WAST - 56533 HIGHWAY 58 WEST - MCKITTRICK CA.  WE REMOVED THE TRAILER TO OUR BAKERSFIELD CA TERMINAL WHERE IT REMAINS PENDING REPAIR. THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WAS THEN DELIVERED TO SOUTH GATE CA AFTER INSPECTION OF THE UNDAMAGED TRUCK REVEALED NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS.

column168: UPON DELIVERY  AT THE FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 2 DRUMS IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER HAD LEAKED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  NO MATERIAL ESCAPED OUTSIDE THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SHIPPER IMPROPERLY LOADED THE TRAILER BY USING TOO MUCH PRESSURE TO MOVE THE DRUMS TO THE NOSE TO MAKE ROOM FOR OTHER CONTAINERS.  LEAK WAS CONTAINED TO A SMALL AREA FACILITY CLEANED IT UP DISPOSED OF MATERIAL AND CLEANUP DEBRIS.

ORIGINAL 55 GALLON DRUM HAD ALREADY EXPERIENCED A SMALL LEAK AT THE SHIPPER PRIOR TO LOADING.  DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85 GALLON METAL DRUM.  WHILE THE LOAD WAS STOPPED IN TRANSIT A SPILL FROM THE OVERPACK WAS DISCOVERED BY OUR YARD PERSONNEL DURING A ROUTINE YARD CHECK.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER TO THE PAVEMENT.  DISCOLORATION OF THE PAVEMENT INDICATED THAT THE RAIN HAD CAUSED THE MATERIAL TO TRAVEL TO A STORM DRAIN (SMALL AMOUNT ). EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE SENT; DRUM WAS REOVERPACKED INTO A 110 GALLON DRUM.  ONLY TRACE AMOUNTS OF THE MATERIAL REMAINED FROM THE SPILL;  AREA WAS CLEANED .  NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO NRC (REPORT 39724)  AND OH EPA (REPORT 9707-57-3047).  DRUM WAS DELIVERED TO FACILITY WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENTS.

UPON UNLOADING AT CONSIGNEE - FORKLIFT DRIVER DUMPED 55 GALLON DRUM OFF PALLET. SMALL CREASE IN SIDE OF DRUM FROM BEING DUMPED. SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID IN CARRIER TRAILER AND SMALL AMOUNT ON CONSIGNEE FLOOR. CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP. NO ROTATION ON BILLS BY CONSIGNEE - INFO AND PICTURES SUPPLIES BY OUR DELIVERY DRIVER.

UPON UNLOADING IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT SOME DRUMS THAT WERE VISIBLE ON REAR OF TRAILER WERE LEAKING AROUND CAPS. THE CONDITION AND QUALITY OF THE DRUMS WERE NOT ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE. DRUM CAPS SEEMED TO HAVE CORROSION AND WEAKNESS AROUND CAP AREA. SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS WIPED UP - CLEANED BY CONSIGNEE. SHIPPER NEEDS TO HAVE A BETTER QUALITY INSPECTION SYSTEM FOR THE DRUMS THEY USE.

ACTION AT DISCOVERY: MCDANIELS NOTIFIED LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCY TO GO TO THE SCENE TO OVERSEE. REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE THEN CONTACTED. ALSO, CONTACTED OUR INSURANCE COMPANY. CHECKED ON OUR DRIVER IN HOSPITAL. CONCLUDED MAKING ARRANGEMENT FOR CLEANUP. ACTION FOR FUTURE: NONE

WHEN HAZMAT DRIVER ARRIVED AT GENERATOR SITE IN ROCKY MOUNT, VA AND OPENED TRAILER DOORS, HE DISCOVERED FUMES INSIDE TRAILER FROM A CONTAINER ALREADY ON THE VAN PICKED UP FROM A PREVIOUS GENERATOR LOCATION. LCM CORPORATION, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR IN ROANOKE, VIRGINIA, WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED AND THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED. ALL CLEANUP DEBRIS AND CONTAMINATED PPE WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE IDENTIFIED ON THE MANIFEST. NO MATERIAL ENTERED ANY DRAINS OR WATERWAYS.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WAST WAS ENROUTE FROM IVAX INDUSTRIES INCORPORATED LOCATED ON ROUTE 95 WEST IN MARION, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL. DURING THE COURSE OF THIS TRIP, THE DRIVER MAD A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND (CHCI) LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH IN ORDER TO TRANSFER MATERIAL FROM HIS VEHICLE TO ANOTHER VEHICLE. DURING THE TRANSFER OPERATION, CHCI PERSONNEL USED A DRUM HANDLING DEVICE KNOWN AS A "PARROT BEAK" TO WHICH PICKS UP A DRUM BY THE UPPER LIP FOR MOVEMENT OF THE DRUM FROM ONE VEHICLE TO ANOTHER. THE ENGAGING PROCESS OF THE PARROT BEAK LATCHING ONTO THE DRUMS PUNCTURED THE TOPS OF TWO DRUMS, CAUSING AN ESCAPE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF OUNCE OF MATERIAL ONTO THE TOPS OF EACH DRUM. THE MATERIAL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED ON THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS AND WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. CHCI PERSONNEL INITIATED A CLEANUP OPERATION. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PLACED ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUMS. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE DRIVER INSPECTED ALL CONTAINERS FOR INTEGRITY. THERE WERE NO VISUAL INDICATORS THAT THE DRUM WOULD FAIL. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO CAREFULLY INSPECT ALL CONTAINERS PRIOR TO ACCEPTANCE. ADDITIONALLY, CHCI PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CAREFULLY INSPECT ALL CONTAINERS PRIOR TO MOVEMENT TO ENSURE CONTAINER INTEGRITY IS MAINTAINED.

SKID OF HAZMAT WAS ON THE DOCK AWAITING TRANSIT. WHEN DOCK WORKER MOVED SKID THREE BAGS WERE RIPPED OPEN. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND PRODUCT IDENTIFIED. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED. HAZMAT TEAM SWEPT MATERIAL UP AND PLACED IT INTO A DRUM ALONG WITH DAMAGED BAGS. DRUM WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT A LATER DATE. REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

THREE PLASTIC PAILS WERE FOUND LEAKING INSIDE THE TRAILER. RELEASE WAS CONTAINED ON THE RIMS OF THE PAILS. HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT TOWELS. WASTE WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM TO BE HELD PENDING DISPOSITION. THE PAILS WERE PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: ON JULY 18, 1997, AT APPROXIMATELY 2129 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, SERIAL NUMBER NATX 71414, LOADED WITH ELEVATED TEMPERATURE, LIQUID, FLAMMABLE, NOS, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING WHILE EN ROUTE AT OUR VEALS, TEXAS LOCATION.  THE TANK CAR OCCASIONALLY EMITTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR WHEN BEING MOVED.  THEREFORE, THE TANK CAR IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE VAPOR RELEASE.  THE SHIPPER, REILLY INDUSTRIES, INC WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT SITE.  THE SHIPPER REPLACED A DEFECTIVE DOME LID GASKET LOCATED ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  AFTER THE SHIPPER COMPLETED FIELD REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR, THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

THE MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND THE VEHICLE WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH ABSORBENT.  TO HELP PREVENT RECURRENCE, THE BOLT RING LID ASSEMBLY ON THE CONTAINERS WILL BE MORE DILIGENTLY EMPLOYED AND INSPECTED.

column168: NO RELIABLE WITNESS HAVE BEEN IDENTIFIED TO SUBSTANTIATE THE CIRCUMSTANCES OF THE ACCIDENT/INCIDENT. DRIVER DIED AS A RESULT OF INJURIES FROM THE ACCIDENT. THERE WERE NO FATALITIES OR INJURIES DUE TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE CARGO TANK WAS NOT PUNCTURED AND THE CARGO RETENTION CAPACITY OF THE TANK DID NOT FAIL. PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE VENT PIPE WHEN THE CARGO TANK WAS ON ITS SIDE. ONLY A LIMITED AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LEAKED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT; HOWEVER, CITY OFFICIALS AND PERSONNEL FROM THE CLEANUP COMPANY DECIDED TO LET AS MUCH PRODUCT AS POSSIBLE DRAIN FROM THE TANK IN ITS OVERTURNED POSITION BEFORE UPRIGHTING THE CARGO TANK. THIS PROCESS AND UPRIGHTING THE TANK TOOK APPROXIMATELY 6-8 HOURS. PRODUCT THAT HAD DRAINED FROM THE TANK COOLED AND SOLIDIFIED, AND WAS LOADED INTO DUMP VEHICLES FOR TRANSPORTATION TO A DISPOSAL LOCATION. TOTAL PRODUCT THAT WAS LOST IS ESTIMATED TO BE 15.21 TONS OR 132 GALLONS.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD, IN BRISTOL, CT. DURING ROUTINE STOPAT A REST AREA IN WESTBOROUGH, MA, THE DRIVER PERFORMED A VEHICLE INSPECTION AND NOTICED A LEAKING CONTAINER. THE DRIVER CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER TO OBTAIN ASSISTANCE. THE LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ALSO NOTIFIED. A CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED FROM OUR BOSTON OFFICE IN ORDER TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ONCE ON SCENE, THE CLEANUP CREW BEGAN THE CLEANUP OPERATION. UPON INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING CONTAINER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM GASKET SEALING THE BARREL TO THE LID WAS MISSING, AND THAT THE PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED THROUGH THAT SEAM.  THE CLEANUP CREW INSTALLED A NEW GASKET ONTO THE DRUM. THEY THEN ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE VISUALLY INSPECTED FOR INTEGRITY. THERE WERE NO VISUAL INDICATORS THAT THE DRUM WOULD FAIL. THE DRIVER AND FACILITY PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO CAREFULLY INSPECT ALL CONTAINERS PRIOR TO ACCEPTANCE.

ON JULY 31, 1997 AT APPROXIMATELY 1440 HOURS, RAIL ROAD TANK CAR, SERIAL NUMBER SCMIX 2377, LOADED WITH ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES, LIQUID, N.O.S. (ETHOXYLATED FATTY OR CYCLIC ALCOHOLS) WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, LOCATED O TOP OF THE TANK CAR, WHILE EN ROUTE APPROACHING THE SHREVEPORT RAIL YARD. THE TANK CAR LEAKED ONLY WHEN MOVE, THEREFORE THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED TO THE SHREVEPORT COOP LEAD TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE SPILLAGE. THE MATERIAL RELEASED ONTO THE TOP PORTION OF THE TANK CAR SHELL AND EVAPORATED BEFORE HITTING THE GROUND. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRANGED FOR IMMEDIATE REPAIR. THE DEFECTIVE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS REPLACED AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION AT 1830 HOURS ON THAT SAME DAY.

column168: I WAS REMOVING GAS FROM SOME OLD UNDERGROUND TANKS AT THE BULK PLANT.  WHEN I REMOVED THE PLUG FROM THE CHECK LOCK FITTING,  IT FAILED TO SEAT WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO FLOW INTO THE ATMOSPHERE UNCONTROLLED.  THE FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED, THEY EVACUATED THE AREA AROUND OUR TERMINAL.  WE ALLOWED THE TANK TO BLOW DOWN TO THE LOW PRESSURE AND THEN PLUGGED THE FITTING TO STOP THE FLOW OF GAS.  THE INCIDENT LASTED ABOUT 2 -  2 1/2 HOURS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, PROPERTY DAMAGE OR LOSS OF LIFE.

ETS WAS ADVISED THAT AN AMOUNT EQUAL TO THE RQ WAS NOT RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  SEE COVER LETTER AND ATTACHMENTS THAT FURTHER OUTLINE THE EVENTS AND FINDINGS.  THE DELAY IN PROCESSING THIS REPORT WAS DUE TO THE TIME INVOLVED IN ACCUMULATING ALL DATA.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY AT 1 RIVER ROAD IN SCHENECTADY, NY TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONY ISLAND AVE IN CHICAGO, IL.  DURING THE COURSE OF THIS TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC (CHCI) LOCATED AT 761 MIDDLE STREET IN BRISTOL, CT IN ORDER TO TRANSFER MATERIAL FROM HIS VEHICLE TO ANOTHER VEHICLE,  CHCI FACILITY PERSONNEL INITIATED THE TRANSFER OPERATION AND NOTICED ONE OF THE CONTAINERS HAD BEGUN TO LEAK AND APPROXIMATELY EIGHT OUNCES OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  CHCI FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE DRIVER INSPECTED ALL CONTAINERS FOR INTEGRITY.  THERE WERE NO VISUAL INDICATORS THAT THE DRUM WOULD FAIL.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN REINSTRUCTED TO CAREFULLY INSPECT ALL CONTAINERS PRIOR TO ACCEPTANCE.

I THEN PUT ON THE PROPER PPE AND TOOK A PH TEST RESULTING IN A 9. I PUT SODIUM BICARBONATE ON THE SPILL TO A PH OF 7. I THEN CLEANED UP THE SPILL USING CLAY BASED ABSORBENT AND TRANSFERRED TO DOT CASE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING THROUGH DMP.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: I WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL BY THE UNLOADER. I SAW THAT IT WAS A CORROSIVE LIQUID SO I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS AND NEUTRALIZED IT WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND CLEANED IT UP WITH FLOOR DRY. I THEN PROCESSED THE SALVAGEABLE PORTION THROUGH THE REPACK PROGRAM AND THE DAMAGED PORTION THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A CORROSIVE LIQUID SPILL IN OUT BAY 694. UPON ARRIVING, THE AREA HAD BEEN EVACUATED BY KEN COLEMAN FULL-TIME SUPERVISOR. DUE TO THE STRONG ODOR BEING GIVEN OFF BY PACKAGE I REFERRED TO MY DECISION TREE WHICH LED ME TO MY CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE. I DONNED MY PPE AND SCBA. I TOOK A PH READING WHICH RESULTED IN A READING OF 12. I NEUTRALIZED THE PRODUCT USING SODIUM BICARBONATE TO A READING OF 7. I THEN TRANSPORTED THE DAMAGE TO THE DOT CASE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING THROUGH DMP. BALANCE RETURNED TO SHIPPER.
NO REMARKS

column168: During the transfer process, several boxes were found to have an oily stain and were emitting a "gas-like" smell.  The boxes were opened and found to contain undeclared and improperly packaged dangerous goods.  The shipment was described as veterinary products and was accompanied by a letter stating the shipment was non-hazardous.  An outside contractor was hired to repackage, label, and document the shipment correctly.  The shipment was terminated by the shipper and consignee and recovered by a consolidator.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: ON 7-9-97 AFTER DEPARTING ONT ENROUTE TO TOL, CLIMBING THROUGH 12,000 FT. GARY TEIPEL, CHECK ENGINEER, SMELLED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA WHILE INVESTIGATING THE SOURCE, WALK AROUND 02 IN HAND.  GARY ENCOUNTERED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA STRONG ENOUGH THAT NEARLY INCAPACITATED HIM.  THE CREW HAD DOWNED 02 MASKS THEN DECLARED AN EMERGENCY, AND RETURNED TO ONT.  IN THE INTEREST OF SAFETY, THE CREW DETERMINED THAT OUR IMMEDIATE RETURN WAS NECESSARY DUE TO THE SEVERITY OF THE FUMES, THEREFORE DUMPING FUEL WAS NOT AN OPTION.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS SUFFICIENT RUNWAY AVAILABLE FOR LANDING UP TO 340,000 LBS. APPROACH, LANDING, AND ROLLOUT WAS NORMAL, BRAKING WAS NORMAL.  AFTER ROLLOUT THE CREW TAXIED TO THE CARGO AREA.

02 JUL97 14.15LCL ON UNLOADING AN AGENT NOTED TANK VENTING STEAM ASSUMING IT WAS DRY ICE, HE PICKED UP THE CONTAINER AND LIQUID NITROGEN SPILLED ON HIS BOOT CAUSING A SMALL BURN ON HIS ANKLE.  AGENT WAS SENT TO HOSPITAL AS PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.  CONTAINER WAS TAKEN TO CARGO AND HELD FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  CONTAINER WAS PROPERLY LABELED AND MARKED.  DURING THIS TIME, THE EMERGENCY GUIDE WAS USED FOR INSTRUCTIONS. THE EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER WAS CALLED AND VERIFIED CONTENTS AND MEASURES TO BE TAKEN.  FAA AND CONSIGNEE WERE NOTIFIED.  BRITISH AIRWAY LONDON NOTIFIED BY TELEX.  AS THIS APPEARS TO BE A CHANCE WELD FAILURE, AND EMERGENCY PROCEDURES PROVED ADEQUATE, DO NOT BELIEVE OTHER CAUTIONARY ACTION SHOULD BE TAKEN WHEN HANDLING GOODS OF THIS NATURE.

column168: DONNED PPE, DECISION TREE, RESPONSE SHEET, UNKNOWN SHEET, PH7, FLAMMABLE LIQUID SHEET, CUT CARDBOARD, BAGGED, TAGGED PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED AT 0230 HOURS THAT TRAIN MKSNP-01 WESTBOUND ON SIDING AT KENEFICK MP 85.25 HAD STRUCK THE SIDE OF TRAIN ZSEME-29 MOVING EASTBOUND ON MAINLINE RESULTING IN DERAILMENT AND FIRE.  DERAILMENT INCLUDED THE 21ST REAR CAR "TTAX -553786" WITH TRAILER "YFSZ-36289" WHICH WAS OVERTURNED HAVING THE TOP OF TRAILER TORN OPEN EXPOSING THE CONTENTS.  THIS PRODUCT WAS IN THE NOSE SECTION AND WAS INTACT EXCEPT FOR SLIGHT CRUSHING OF THE BOTTOM CARTONS.  THE ONLY LEAKAGE NOTED WAS A SLIGHT DAMPNESS ON SEVERAL OF THE CARDBOARD CARTONS APPARENTLY SEEPAGE FROM THE LID DURING THE OVERTURNING MOVEMENT.  WAYBILL INFORMATION INDICATED THE FOLLOWING; "53/CTM 2090LBS PESTICIDE LIQUID, TOXIC,N.O.S. (ABAMETICIN SOLUTION) 6.1 UN2902 PG 111, EMERGENCY CONTACT 800-424-9300 HAZMAT STCC 4925270".  ALSO 55 CTN PESTICIDES LIQUID TOXIC, N.O.S.(ABAMETICIN SOLUTION) 6.1 UN2902,111,  24 HOUR EMERGENCY 800-424-9300 2090LBS".  THE FIRST ENTRY ON THE WAYBILL SHOWED "55/CTM, 2110 LB BROMINE CHLORIDE (ABAMETICIN SOLUTION) 2.3 (5,1,8) UN2901 POISON-INHALATION HAZARD ZONE B EMERGENCY CONTACT; 800-424-9300 HAZMAT STCC= 4920715", HOWEVER THIS PRODUCT WAS NOT ON THIS TRAILER.  TO PREVENT ANY RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL THE CARTONS WERE HAND UNLOADED AND PLACED IN AN ISOLATED AREA WHERE HAZ-MAT RESPONSE INC. PLACED GOOD CASES ON PALLETS AND STRETCH WRAPPED WAS APPLIED.  AND OF THE CARTONS THAT WERE TORN OR SHOWED ANY STAINING WERE PLACED IN 4-55 GALLON OPEN TOP STEEL DRUM.  THE FOUR DRUMS CONTAINED A TOTAL OF 57 JUGS AND THE CARDBOARD CARTONS.  JULY 4, 1997  THE RECOVERED MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI FREIGHT HOUSE.  JULY 11, 1997 YELLOW FREIGHT PICKED UP THE MATERIAL FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE WHICH IS MERCK AGVET 4545 OLEATHA AVE ST. LOUIS, MO.  EDI BILLING FROM YELLOW FREIGHT SHOWED ONLY THE 108 CARTONS OF PESTICIDES AS DESCRIBED AND FREIGHT ALL KINDS.

WHILE LOADING, ONE PAIL OF PRODUCT WAS PIERCED BY A FORKLIFT. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE PRODUCT IDENTIFIED. ROADWAY PERSONNEL USED A BASE NEUTRAL ZERO ON THE SPILLAGE AND THEN SWEPT UP THE MATERIAL, PLACING IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM WITH THE DAMAGED PAIL. THE DEBRIS WILL BE HELD FOR LOCAL DISPOSAL AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.

column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D. A. LOW, WAS ADVISED BY CHEYENNE CARMAN, THAT A STRONG ODOR OF ETHER WAS COMING FROM TANK CARS EAST END OF SOUTH THREE TRACK, CHEYENNE.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, ALSO VALVE WAS OPEN ONE COMPLETE TURN.  PROPERLY SECURED VALVE AND PACKING, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  WENDELL STEWART, COASTAL CHEM, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION E.M.G. HARRY W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY TRAILER RAMP PERSONNEL ABOUT LEAKING TRAILER CONTAINER RDWZ237717.  MGR. RODABOUGH HAD THE CONTAINER ISOLATED IN THE YARD.  HE OPENED THE CONTAINER, REMOVED THE PACKING LISTS FOR IDENTIFICATION PURPOSES, AND INSPECTED THE LOAD, FINDING NO BLOCKING OR BRACING. THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED MAKING ENTRY INTO THE CONTAINER DIFFICULT. THE MATERIAL HAD AN ODOR OF PESTICIDE.  MGR. RODABOUGH CONTACTED ROADWAY EXPRESS, INFORMING THEM OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES.  THEY CALLED T.W. CO. OF 505 NORTH MAIN, SALT LAKE, UT TO REMEDIATE THE CONTAMINATED CONTAINER.  MR. JOSEPH D. PARKINSON, HAZ TECH SERVICE MANAGER FOR T. W. ARRIVED AT THE SIGHT AT 1450  HOURS. THE RAIL CAR WAS CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED, THEN THEY TURNED THEIR ATTENTION TO THE CONTAINER, REMOVING THE LADING UNTIL THEY FOUND THE PROBLEM.  THEY DISCOVERED THAT TWO OF THE FIVE GALLON CANS HAD BEEN CRUSHED, CAUSING THEM TO LOSE MOST OF THEIR CONTENTS, BEING THE PESTICIDE. ALL REMEDIATION EFFORTS WERE COMPLETE AT 1930 HRS.  ON 070297, CHEMTREC MR. MIKE MURPHY WAS FURNISHED WITH THE DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE #56517.  THE SHIPPER HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN NOTIFIED.

column168: ON 7/1/97 A SPILL WAS REPORTED BY THE RAMP LEAD.  THE LOCATION WAS GATE DELTA 52, TAIL #N979AZ, IN BELLY ONE.  THIS WAS AN ODOR ONLY.  THE LOCATION WAS ABX AIR, INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILIMINGTON, OHIO 45177. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON AND PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS SUE HICKEY AND CARL BOHL RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL A FIBERBOARD BOX WAS FOUND AND EMITTING AN "GASOLINE" ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE A METAL SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WHICH WAS LOOSE. APPROXIMATELY 1/2 OZS OF "GASOLINE" WAS LOST.

UPRR SWITCH CREW, ALFALFA YARD EL PASO, REPORTED TANK CAR RPBX 23216 WAS LEAKING.  THE CAR HAD BEEN PICKED UP FROM THE CHEVRON PLANT AND HAD NOT BEEN RECEIVED AT THE YARD WHEN THE LEAK WAS NOTED.  CHEVRON WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THEY FOUND THE LIQUID LINE CAP WAS CRACKED.  THIS WAS REPLACED AND SECURED.  APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  THIS WAS NEUTRALIZED IN PLACE BY CHEVRON.  THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE CHEVRON FACILITY.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED BY CHEVRON.  NO WAYBILL WAS GENERATED FOR THIS CAR MOVEMENT.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH NOTED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF TANK CAR GATX 74048, WHICH WAS A LOADED CAR OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  INSPECTION REVEALED BROKEN FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT,  MOUNTED ON THE MANWAY COVER.  MGR. RODABOUGH REPLACED THE BS&B 100 POUND DISC WITH A LIKE DISC.  CHEMTREC, MR. MIKE MURPHY WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE #56721.  MR. KEITH FRECH OF EL ATOCHEM, SERVICES (215-419-7099)  WAS ALSO INFORMED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: BEING THE UNLOADER I DISCOVERED LEAKING PACKAGE IN TRAILER.  AFTER PUTTING ON PROPER PPE AND RETRIEVING SPILL CART, I FOLLOWED THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEETS.  I TOOK A PH READING OF 2 NEUTRALIZED IT TO A 7 USING SODIUM BICARBONATE.  THEN SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS PUT IN SPILL TUB ALONG WITH PACKAGE AND BROUGHT TO DMP CAGE WHERE IT WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.  PACKAGE SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN LOADED ON SIDE.
WEARING PPE CONSULTED DECISION TREE. FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEETS, DISPOSED OF THRU DMP.  DECONTAMINATED PPE.

column42: EXPLOSIVE, BLASTING, TYPE E OR EXPLOSIVE, AGENT BLASTING, TYPE E
column168: THE ROUTE PLAN TAKEN BY THE DRIVER KENNY JONES WAS AS FOLLOWS. LEAVING THE MINERAL CITY, OHIO STATE LOCATION, KENNY TRAVELED WEST ON COUNTY ROAD 110 TO NORTH BOUND ROUTE 800. THEN NORTH BOUND INTERSTATE 77 TO WEST BOUND ROUTE 30. THEN TO NORTH BOUND ROUTE 23 AND 15 TO EAST BOUND ROUTE 330 AND INTO THE VANLUE, OHIO SITE LOCATION. KENNY INDICATED HE SECURED THE LOAD AND LOCKED THE DOOR WITH A PAD LOCK UPON LEAVING THE MINERAL CITY LOCATION. PASSING THROUGH THE WOOSTER, OHIO AREA, HE WAS FOLLOWED BY STATE HIGHWAY PATROL FOR ABOUT 2 MILES WITHOUT ANY INDICATION OF A PROBLEM. TURNING ONTO THE ROUTE 30 BYPASS AROUND BUCYRUS, OHIO, KENNY SAID HE MADE EYE CONTACT WITH A P.U.C. O. OFFICER WHICH HAD A TRACTOR-TRAILER RIG PULLED TO THE SIDE FOR AN INSPECTION AND AGAIN THERE WAS NO INDICATION BY THE OFFICER THAT A PROBLEM WAS OCCURRING. HE THEN STOPPED IN CRESTLINE, OHIO, WHICH IS APPROXIMATELY 48 MILES FROM HIS DESTINATION, TO CHECK HIS TIRES AND INDICATED THE DOORS WERE SECURE AT THAT TIME. KENNY SAID HE HAS NO INDICATION THAT THE DOOR HAD COME OPEN UNTIL HE TURNED INTO THE ENTRANCE AT THE VANLUE SITE. AS SOON AS HE DISCOVERED THE OPEN DOOR, HE STOPPED AND FOUND A PACKAGE LYING BEHIND THE TRAILER. HE FELT THE DOOR HAD JUST COME OPEN AT THAT POINT BECAUSE OF THE DROP OFF FROM THE PUBLIC HIGHWAY TO THE SITE ENTRANCE AND THE FACT THE LOAD LOCKING DEVICES WERE STILL IN PLACE. THE BOARD USED TO BLOCK AND SECURE THE LOAD AHEAD OF THE LOAD LOCKS HAD BEEN BROKEN SOME HOW. THE PRODUCT WAS LEAVING ITS ORIGINAL PLACEMENT THROUGH THIS OPENING. THE FIRST POLY WOVEN BAG WAS REPORTED BY A PERSON TO THE HANCOCK COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT AT ABOUT 07:52 AM. KENNY ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION AROUND 07:00 AM. AN INVENTORY AT THE CARGO INDICATED ELEVEN OF THE BAGS WERE MISSING. A SEARCH OF THE ROUTE BY COMPANY REPRESENTATIVES, STATE HIGHWAY PATROL, A PATROL HELICOPTER, P.U.C.O., AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES, DISCOVERED 9 BAGS WITHIN 8 MILES OF THE DRIVERS DESTINATION. ONE OF THE PACKAGES HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY A PASSING MOTOR VEHICLE. THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE DUE TO THE FALL FROM THE TRAILER UNIT. AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT, NINE OF THE ELEVEN PACKAGES WERE FOUND. FOUR IN HANCOCK COUNTY AND FIVE IN WYANDOT COUNTY. PREPARATIONS ARE ALREADY UNDERWAY TO SECURE EACH TRAILER IN THE FLEET BY BOLTING OR WELDING AN ADDITIONAL STRIP OF METAL TO OVERLAP FROM THE PASSENGER SIDE DOOR TO THE DRIVERS SIDE DOOR. THIS EXTRA OVERLAP WOULD RE QUIRE THE DRIVERS SIDE DOOR OF THE TRAILER, WHICH WAS THE DOOR THAT OPENED, TO BECOME UN-HINDGED IN ORDER TO OPEN AS LONG AS THE PASSENGER DOOR REMAINED LATCHED AND CLOSED. NO REASONABLE EXPLANATION HAS BEEN DETERMINED AS TO HOW OR WHY THIS DOOR COULD HAVE OPENED WHEN THE TOP AND BOTTOM LATCH MECHANISM WAS IN PLACE WHEN THE VEHICLE LEFT IT'S ORIGIN AND THE HANDLE WHICH CONTROLS THE LATCHING MOVEMENT WAS STILL IN IT'S LOCKED POSITION WHEN THE DRIVER FIRST DISCOVERED THE DOOR HAD OPENED.

column168: ON OPERATIONS DATE 07/09/97, I BEN TAYLOR WAS NOTIFIED OF A PACKAGE LEAKING A TYPE OF OIL IN BLDG "C" AT THE REWRAP AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY, LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. UPON ARRIVAL I FOUND THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND FOUND THAT THE PACKAGE WAS SATURATED AND APPEARED TO BE OILY. I VISUALLY INSPECTED THE OUTERMOST PACKAGING FOR ANY TYPE OF MARKINGS OR LABELS, BUT DID NOT FIND ANY AT ALL THAT WOULD INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS IN THE PACKAGE MIGHT BE A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. I THEN OPENED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND TWO INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES, ONE OF WHICH APPEARED TO BE LEAKING. I ALSO NOTICED THAT BOTH INNER FIBERBOARD BOXED WERE PRESTAMPED ""THIS SIDE UP", BUT DUE TO THEIR HEIGHT WERE PLACED ON THEIR SIDES AGAINST ORIENTATION, WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO ONE OF THE INNER PLASTIC TO LEAK. ALSO FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE INNER PLASTIC RECEPTACLES REVEALED THAT ON THE RECEPTACLE THE CLOSURE WAS NOT PROPERLY APPLIED. BOTH INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES EACH CONTAINED 3X2 QUARTS EACH OF "NAPHTHA, HYDROTREATED HEAVY" NONE OF THE INNER PLASTIC RECEPTACLES CLOSURES WERE SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THE SHIPMENT WAS PUT INTO A PLASTIC BAG AND WE RETURNED TO THE HAZMAT SORT BUILDING AND REPACKED IT INTO A UN1A1 SALVAGE DRUM THEN PLACED IT INTO OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY. ONCE THE SHIPMENT HAS BEEN INVESTIGATED BY THE AUTHORITIES IT WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR REQUEST. THE SHIPMENT WILL BE RETURNED VIA HIGHWAY ACCORDING TO APPLICABLE REGULATIONS SET FORTH BY TITLE 49CFR.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION BY THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED SEVERAL HOUSE HOLD ITEMS. SEVERAL MAY HAVE LEAKED. THE SHIPPER USED A PLASTIC BAS AS THE OUTER PACKAGE AND PLACED MANY HOUSEHOLD CLEANERS ETS. IN THE BAG. THE INNER CONTAINERS WERE MADE OF VARIOUS MATERIALS, PLASTIC, METAL ETC. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED THREE 50OZ TIDE, TWO 16OZ CINCH, ONE 50 OZ DREFT, TWO 20 OZ DOWNEY, TWO PUMP SPRAY WINDEX, ONE 22 OZ CLOROX AND 32 OZ CLOROX, FOUR 14 OZ MR CLEAN, TWO 20OZ MR CLEAN, TWO BOTTLES OF SHAMPOO, ONE 10 OZ SOFT SCRUB, HAND CLEANER, AS WELL AS THE FOLLOWING TWO ITEMS, ONE PVC CEMENT , MANUFACTURER OATEY, PRODUCT #30782 AND ONE PVC CLEANER, MANUFACTURER OATEY, PRODUCT CODE #31013. WE SUSPECTED NON DECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SO I PHONED THE MANUFACTURER AND HAD MSDS'S FOR THE LAST TOW PRODUCTS FAX TO ME . BOTH APPEAR TO BE NON-DECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, FLAMMABLE LIQUID UNDER IATA STANDARDS. THE PVC CEMENT IS BELIEVED TO BE "ADHESIVES", UN1133. THE PVC CLEANER IS BELIEVED TO BE EITHER "CONSUMER COMMODITY" ID 8000 OR FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S." UN 1993. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED.  UPON INSPECTION BY THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST IT WAS FOUND TO BE BANANA EXTRACT.  I PHONED THE SHIPPER TO OBTAIN A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS) WHICH THEY FAX'D TO ME (SEE ENCLOSED).  THE FLASH POINT WAS 92 DEGREES FARENHEIT CLOSED CUP.  THIS FALLS UNDER THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAZARD CLASS UNDER IATA STANDARDS.  I REPORTED THIS AS A NON-DECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT TO FAA INSPECTOR RAY WHALEN AT (718) 553-3122.  THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  A CARTON CONTAINING 51 LBS (23 K) CADMIUM PIGMENTS WAS SHIPPED VA 943 CDG ORD 1588121 JUL ORDCLE.  TOP OF BOX WAS NOT SEALED AND PARTIALLY BENT BACK REVEALING LABEL WHICH CONTAINED WARNING THAT CADMIUM MAY BE DANGEROUS.  CLEFF AIR, WHO OBSERVED WARNING NOTICE, CONTACTED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HOT LINE AND WAS TOLD TO CONTACT A SUPERVISOR, WHO THEN CONTACTED FIRE DEPARTMENT AND FAA SPECIAL REP HODGE MORTON AT 265-1530.  THIS WAS 7122  AT APPROXIMATELY 1800. FIRE PREVENTION BUREAU, LT ZAKORDONIZ, HAD MATERIAL PLACED IN HAZ MAT DRUM CONTAINER AND EVACUATED CARGO BUILDING FOR APPROXIMATELY 1.25 HOURS.  FAA REP REPORTED TO SCENE BUT MATERIAL HAD BEEN STOWED IN CONTAINER BY THAT TIME SO HE WAS UNABLE TO TAKE PHOTOGRAPHS WHICH HE NEEDS.  AT THIS TIME CONSIGNEE HAS BEEN ADVISED OF SITUATION AND WILL IN TURN ADVISE SARTOMER COMPANY IN EXTON, PA WHO WAS ULTIMATE ADDRESSEE.  ALSO FAA REP HODGE MORTON WILL CONTACT CHEMTRON CORPORATION, WHO IS HAZ MAT DISPOSER COMPANY USED BY VAL IN CLEVELAND.  CHEMTRON WILL OPEN CONTAINER SO THAT FAA REP CAN GET PHOTOS OF CONTENTS.  CHEMTRON WILL THEN DISPOSE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  NOTE: ALSO ON LETTER OF TRANSPORT IS MESSAGE TO NOTIFY TEKNOR COLOR, 120 WEST DRIVE, LODI, OH 330-948-2035.  ON MONDAY, JULY 28TH, TWO REPRESENTATIVES FROM CHEMTRON CORPORATION CAME TO UNITED AIRLINES CLEVELAND CARGO FACILITY AND REMOVED SUBJECT CONTENTS FROM THE HAZARDOUS CONTAINMENT DRUM SO THAT FAA SPECIAL REPRESENTATIVE HODGE MORTON WAS ABLE TO TAKE PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE PACKAGE.  MATERIAL HAS SINCE BEEN DELIVERED TO TEKNOR CORPORATION. THE FAA REPRESENTATIVE CONFIRMED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS HAZARDOUS AND, AS A RESULT, WE ARE SUBMITTING THIS REPORT.  UNITED IS FILING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL AVIATION REGULATIONS PART 175.45.  UNITED MAKES NO DETERMINATION OF ADMISSION BY VIRTUE OF THIS FILING AS TO THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT.

THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT IN A PASSENGER'S CHECKED BAG. FLIGHT 594 ARRIVED IN SEA AND RAMP AGENT BEGIN UNLOADING THE FORWARD BIN OF THE AIRCRAFT.  WHEN THE AGENT TOOK HOLD OF THIS BACKPACK HE NOTICED SMOKE AND A SMALL HOLE IN THE FRONT POCKET OF THE BACKPACK.  THE HOLE WAS SMOLDERING AND GROWING LARGER AND A SMALL FLAME ERUPTED FROM THE BACKPACK.  THE AGENT BEGIN TO PAT THE FLAME AND REMOVING THE BAG FROM THE BIN SIMULTANEOUSLY.  THE SMOLDERING FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED ON THE RAMP.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT ELKO, NV. MGR H.W. RODABOUGH NOTED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF TANK CAR SP 67320. INVESTIGATION REVEALED BOTH THE LIQUID AND THE AIR VALVES LOCATED INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON TOP OF THE CAR, WERE LOOSE. AMBIENT TEMPERATURE CAUSED THE CAR TO SELF PRESSURIZE, FORCING THE LIQUID UP THE EDUCATION PIPE AND OUT AROUND THE LOOSE VALVES. MGR. RODABOUGH REMOVED BOTH THE ONE INCH AIR VALVE AND THE TWO INCH LIQUID VALVE ASSEMBLIES AND TAPED THE FITTINGS WITH TEFLON TAPE AND THEN SECURED THE VALVES. CHEMTREC, MR. LIEF ERICSON, FURNISHED WITH THE DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 58036. THE SHIPPER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE EXCEPTIONS.

AT 1345HRS ON 7/30/97, SR SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT T.J. BOURDREAUX RECEIVED A TELEPHONE CALL FROM CAR FOREMAN MARK BARRIOS WHO ADVISED THAT TANK CAR GATX 94427 WAS UNDER THE RIP TRACK SHED AND LEAKING AMMONIA. BOUDREAUX ARRIVED AT 1400 HRS. AND BEGAN INSPECTING TANK CAR. UPON OPENING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, AN ODOR OF AMMONIA WAS DETECTED. THE VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE CHECKED WITH SNOOP. A LEAK WAS DETECTED AT THE BASE OF THE A END LIQUID VALVE. THE NUTS AT THE BASE OF THE VALVE WERE CHECKED AND ONE NUT WAS TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 3/4 OF A TURN, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE CONSIGNEE, TRIAD CHEMICAL'S STEVE MISTRETTA WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF AGENT BOUDREAUX FINDINGS AND ACTION.

ON 72997 AT APPROXIMATELY 7AM MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A REPORT THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING. UPON ARRIVAL REEDER EXAMINED THE CAR AND FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE B END. SINCE THIS IS A JACKETED CAR, THE EXACT SOURCE OF THE LEAK COULD NOT BE DETERMINED. THE LEAK RATE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 DROP EVERY 2-3 SECONDS AND VARIED GREATLY OVER TIME. A BUCKET PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CATCH THE LEAK COLLECTED ABOUT ONE GALLON OVER SEVERAL HOURS. CODE 3 EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS HIRED TO TRANSFER THE LOAD INTO TRUCKS. THE MATERIAL WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED FOR DISPOSAL. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED BY THE COMMUNICATIONS CENTER IN DENVER. (INFORMATION WAS NOT AVAILABLE FROM RMCC).

REGIONAL MANAGER TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, SPARKS, NV., WAS NOTIFIED BY SPECIAL AGENT VERN LIBBY, SEATTLE, WA., THAT TRAILER BMDZ633412, BILLED CONTAIN METHANOL AND SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, AND OTHER FREIGHT OF ALL KINDS WAS LEAKING AT ALBINA YARD, PORTLAND, OR. OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ENROUTE TO INSPECT AND STABILIZE LOAD. THEY FOUND PALLET OF SHRINK WRAPPED 5 GALLON BUCKETS NOSE OF TRAILER STACKED 3 BUCKETS HIGH. THE WEIGHT OF THE TOP BUCKETS HAD CRUSHED THE LIDS OF THE BOTTOM TIER RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE TRAILER WAS STABILIZED AND DAMAGED BUCKETS WERE TRANSFERRED INTO RECOVERY CONTAINERS. THE TRAILER WAS THEN MOVED TO CONSIGNEE OVERNIGHT TRUCKING WHO FOUND 9 BUCKETS FROM SHIPMENT OF 48 HAD BEEN DAMAGED. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ROUGH HANDLING OF THIS SHIPMENT. OVERNIGHT CONTACTS KENT KLINEDINST, PORTLAND, OR. AND JACKIE WIDENER, RICHMOND VA., 804/231-8203.

LEAKING FORM PROTECTIVE HOUSING ATOP OF TANK CAR.  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AT WEST END OF OLD AUTO RAMP LEAD.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TOP UNLOADING ARRANGEMENT FLANGE HAD 9 OUT OF 9 BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. CLEANED FLANGE AND TIGHTENED BOLTS, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  ALSO, FIBERGLASSED FLANGE. JOE BABER, CHEMTREC, FILE NUMBER 57838  AND BRENT KRILEY, FINA, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT SEAL FINA-18871 WAS REMOVED SO REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. AT 0730 HRS., ON 07/24/97, SR. SPECIAL AGENT T. M. BOUDREAUX RECEIVED INFORMATION FROM MTO JEFF JONES WHO REPORTED THAT NUMEROUS EMPLOYEES WERE COMPLAINING ABOUT AN UNKNOWN ODOR IN AND AROUND THE AVONDALE YARD.  AT 0810 HRS., AGENT BOUDREAUX ARRIVED IN THE AVONDALE YARD AND BEGAN SEARCHING FOR THE SOURCE OF THE UNKNOWN ODOR.  AT 1050 HRS., CARMAN G. E. SMITH CONTACTED AGENT BOUDREAUX AND REPORTED THAT HE HAD LOCATED A TANK CAR, CELX 23140, ON TRACK #38 IN THE SOUTH YARD, THAT WAS LEAKING. AGENT BOUDREAUX LOCATED THE LEAKING TANK CAR AND NOTED THAT THE VAPOR THAT WAS LEAKING WAS THE SAME ODOR REPORTED EARLIER BY THE EMPLOYEES.  AN INSPECTION WAS MADE OF THE TANK CAR'S CLOSURES.  SEAL HOECHST CELANESE-TX 74139 WAS REMOVED FROM VALVE PROTECTIVE COVER.  THE PLUGS ON THE AIR AND LIQUID VALVES WERE FOUND LOOSE.  THE LIQUID PLUG WAS REMOVED AND PIPE TAPE WAS ADDED.  BOTH PLUGS WERE THEN TIGHTENED.  THE FOUR (4) BOLTS ON THE VALVE PLUG FLANGES OF THE AIR AND LIQUID VALVES WERE FOUND LOOS.  THE FLANGE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED.  THE PROTECTIVE COVER WAS CLOSED AND SEAL UNION PACIFIC F-482420 WAS APPLIED TO THE LOCKING PIN.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS FOUND THAT THE PLUG ON THE AUXILIARY VALVE WAS LOOSE.  THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED. THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE LEVER KEEPER PIN WAS NOT PROPERLY APPLIED. THE PIN WAS APPLIED PROPERLY, LOCKING THE VALVE LEVER AND APPLYING SEAL UNION PACIFIC F-482421.  WITH THE ESCAPING VAPOR STOPED THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: UPRR CAR INSPECTOR J. SPENCER REPORTED THAT THERE WAS A FOUL ODOR AROUND TANK CAR UTLX202024. column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON THURSDAY, JULY 17, 1997 AT 12OO HOURS, SPECIAL AGENT E.R. FEDRICK RECEIVED A CALL FROM SYO JIMMY MARTINEZ AT REISOR YARD IN SHREVEPORT, LA ADVISING TANKCAR TILX 100139 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP. FEDRICK ARRIVED ON THE SCENE ALONG WITH LA DEQ AGENT MIKE DEERE AND LA STATE POLICE HAZMAT SGT ED BOBBIT. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED CAUSING THE TANKCAR TO LEAK WHEN IT WAS MOVED. FEDRICK REPLACED THE FRANGIBLE DISC AND MIKE DEERE SPREAD LIME ON THE SMALL AMOUNT OF DPILL ON THE TANKCAR AND THE GROUND. THE CAR WAS THEN RETURNED TO SERVICE. FEDERICK SPOKE WITH SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, TED KALAGIAN, AT MARSULEX IN CHICAGO, IL. HE ADVISED HIM OF THE INCIDENT AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN.

ON 07 1697 AT APPROXIMATELY 645 AM, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER WAS NOTIFIED OF A TRAIN DERAILMENT AT INARI SIDING. ELEVEN CARS HAD DERAILED WITH SOME OF THEM BEING OVERTURNED, CELX22030 WAS OFF ITS TRUCK AND PARTIALLY BURIED IN THE BALLAST. THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY HAD BEEN SHEARED OFF. THE VALVE INSIDE THE CAR WAS NOT DAMAGED.  HOWEVER, PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT THE RATE OF ABOUT ONE DROP EVERY 10 SECONDS. WHEN THE CAR WAS RERAILED, THE LEAK WAS PATCHED AND THE CAR MOVED TO A SAFE LOCATION FOR TRANSFER. THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH A BASIC SOLUTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE CALEXICO FIRE DEPARTMENT, REPORTING TANK CAR GATX97441 WAS VENTING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SITE AND HAD SET UP WATER LINES TO KNOCK DOWN THE VAPORS FROM THE CAR. DUE TO THE EXTREME HEAT IN THE AREA DURING THE WEEK, THE PRODUCT WAS EXPANDING CAUSING THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE TO OPERATE. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO CALEXICO AND MET WITH THE TRANSFER VEHICLE ARRANGED THROUGH THE SHIPPER. A PORTION OF THE LIQUID WAS REMOVED FROM THE CAR TO ALLOW FOR GREATER VAPOR SPACE THUS REDUCING THE PROBABILITY OF FURTHER RELEASES. ONE COMPLETED, THE CAE WAS RESECURED FOR MOVEMENT. NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE CALEXICO FIRE DEPARTMENT, ADVISING THEY HAD LOCATED TANK CAR GATX89953, IN STORAGE TRACK 622, AND FOUND IT TO BE LEAKING FROM THE 'A' END LIQUID VALVE, A STANDARD ANGLE BALL VALVE, HAD ICED UP, AND BY MOVING THE OPERATING HANDLE, SECURED THE LEAK. IT APPEARS THE VALVE WAS ASKEW ALLOWING A SLIGHT BY PASS OF PRODUCT. THE PORT PLUG WAS ALSO LOOSE ENOUGH THAT IT COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT FORCED ALIGNED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PORT PLUG WHICH SECURED THE LEAK. NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY TODD VERRILL, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YEMO, CALIFORNIA, WHO STARTED THE CAR DEPARTMENT FORCES WERE INSPECTING AN OUTBOUND TRAIN IN YARD TRACK #208, AND OBSERVED TANK CAR TBOX 2956 TO BE DRIPPING A YELLOW COLORED LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. AS THE CAR WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE, IT WAS LEFT IN PLACE WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER  DROVE TO THE YEMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE LIQUID LINE BLIND FLANGE CONNECTION. ONE OF THE 4" X 5/8" BOLTS THAT SECURES THE BLIND FLANGE WAS SO DETERIORATED THAT THERE WERE NO THREADS REMAINING FOR THE NUT TO TIGHTEN AGAINST. THE BOLT AND NUT WERE REPLACED IN ORDER TO SECURE THE FLANGE. AN ADJACENT FLANGE BOLT WAS ALSO FOUND TO BE ONLY FINGER TIGHT. AFTER TIGHTENING ALL OF THE FLANGE BOLTS, THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: AT 0830 HRS YARDMASTER CALLED AND ADVISEDD THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS EMITTING A LARGE VAPOR CLOUD FROM THE TOP. THE CAR WAS REMOVED FROM THE BOWL TRACK AND ISOLATED NEAR THE FREIGHT HOUSE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY CTS MGR. KELLY IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE TWO BOLTS LOOSE ON THE FLANGE BELOW THE LIQUID LOADING LINE. KELLY TIGHTENED THE TWO BOLTS AND RELEASED THE CAR TO CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

MGR. CTS RICHARD TUFTS WAS NOTIFIED BY MTO ROD RICHARDSON AT 1140 HRS ON 7/7/97 THAT ISO CONTAINER UPTU 660203 WAS LEAKING AT DUPO, IL. MANAGER TUFTS RESPONDED FROM CHICAGO, CONTACTING REG. MR W.M. SEABAUGH, WHO IN TURN ADVISED THE RISK MANAGEMENT DISPATCH CENTER AND REQUESTED PROPER STATE AND CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION MGR. TUFTS MET WITH ILLINOIS EPA EMERGENCY RESPONSE REPRESENTATIVE TOM POWELL, AND THEY MADE AN INSPECTION  OF THE LEAKING TANK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY COVER HAD BEEN LEFT UNSECURED AFTER LOADING, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT OF THE MANWAY AND DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CONTAINER. MR POWELL AGREED THAT AFTER PROPER SECUREMENT OF THE MANWAY, THE SURFACE OF THE GROUND WHERE LEAKAGE HAD POOLED SHOULD BE SCRAPED AND COLLECTED FOR DISPOSAL. ALSO, THE INVOLVED CONTAINER AND ADJACENT CONTAINER SHOULD BE WIPED  CLEAN WITH CLEANUP RAGS AND EFFULENT PROPERLY COLLECTED FOR DISPOSAL. FINALLY, AND PRODUCT REMAINING ON THE RAIL CAR SHOULD BE PROPERLY CLEANED UP. MGR. TUFTS ADVISED SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, MR. DAVID DRAKE, CHAMPION TECHNOLOGIES, MIDLAND, TX. TO ARRANGE FOR A LOCAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INITIATE CLEANUP. MR. DRAKE MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH KIESEL CO., ST. LOUIS TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. MGR. TUFTS, ALONG WITH MGR. ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, MARK SCHAFER REMAINED ON THE SCENE UNTIL THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETE. MGR. TUFTS NOTIFIED STEVE WHITAKER, UP BULKTAINER OPERATIONS CONCERNING RELEASE FROM THE ISOTAINER.

column168: I DISCOVERED PACKAGE THEN TRANSPORTED PACKAGE TO REWRAP AREA AND DONNED PPE THEN REFERRED TO DECISION TREE THEN TO FLAMMABLE LIQUID  RESPONSE SHEETS, REPACKED REMAINS CONTENTS AND FORWARD .
DONNED PPE, DECISION TREE, THEN TO FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEETS, TIGHTENED LOOSE CAP, DISPOSED OF EMPTY BOX THROUGH CESQG, FORWARDED REMAINING CONTENTS.

THE EMPLOYEE THAT DISCOVERED THE WET PACKAGE FOLLOWED PROCEDURE BY NOTIFYING A SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR THEN CONTACTED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER ON DUTY. THE RESPONDER RESPONDED TO THE CALL WEARING PROPER P.P.E. FOLLOWING ECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED. THE STAINED CARDBOARD WAS THEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE THE DMP PROGRAM. ONLY 2 OZ WAS LEAKED FROM CONTAINER. A SPOT THE SIZE OF A QUARTER IS WHAT MAE THE MEPLOEE REALIZE THE PACKAGE COULD BE LEAKING. CAPS SHOULD BE SECURED AND TAPED PRIOR TO SHIPPING.

column168: ON JULY 29, 1997 AT 18:30 HOURS RECEIVED A CALL FROM STEVE PAUL FROM THE RMCC THAT MYO THOMAS LALLY HAD REPORTED THAT TWO CARMEN WERE OVERCOME BY VAPORS FROM TANK CAR. GATX 64595 AT THE PROVISO NORTH YARD.  ONE OF THE CAMEN REPORTED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN VENTING.  THE NORTHLAKE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM SHUT DOWN THE YARD UNTIL THE SITUATION COULD BE REMEDIED.  RESPONDED AT 20:10 AND AFTER AN INSPECTION OF THE CAR, DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS NO LONGER VENTING AND THE NORTHLAKE ER TEAM AGREED TO ALLOW YARD TO RETURN TO NORMAL OPERATIONS.  OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL DISPATCHED A STRIKE TEAM THAT ARRIVED THE NEXT MORNING.  THE STRIKE TEAM INSPECTED THE CAR AND CONCLUDED THAT THE CAR WAS OVER PRESSURE AND THAT THE CONSIGNEE, PPG INDUSTRIES HAD LIKELY OVER PRESSURED THE CAR WITH NITROGEN DURING THE UNLOADING OF THE CAR. MOVEMENT OF THE CAR THEN RESULTED IN THE ACTIVATION OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, RELEASING PRESSURE.  THE BULK OF THE RELEASE WOULD HAVE BEEN NITROGEN.  THE CAR WAS OK'D FOR MOVEMENT BY OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL AND IT WAS MOVED TO THEIR FACILITY IN BAYTOWN, TX.
